{
  "texts": [
    "Clearly ca(I, A) ≡ c A 0 (I, A).",
    "Proposition 1.5.5 Let a = ( (I, A, (A i))), where A ⊂ P(I).",
    "The following are equivalent:(i) a is canonical, (ii) ∀s ∈ A, π a (s) = s, equivalently π a is the inclusion i A ∶ A ↪ P(I),(iii)⌢ A s = {s} for all s ∈ A, and Ās = ∅ for all s ∈ P(I) ∖ A.Corollary 1.5.6 Let K ∈ P 2 (I).",
    "There is a unique canonical p-site a such that κ a = K, precisely ca(I, K).",
    "and a ′ = ( (I, A ′, (A ′ i))) be two p-sites with the same base I. f is said to be an isotopy of a to a ′ if f is a bijection and f(A i) = A ′ i (i ∈ I).If f is an isotopy of a to a ′ then its inverse f -1 is an isotopy of a ′ to a."
  ]
